Benchmarking.CarbonPathwaysIntro:
bZero utilises data from a SBTi aligned tool called CRREM (Carbon Risk Real Estate Monitor). It derives science-based decarbonisation pathways by breaking down the global anthropogenic GHG emissions budget that is consistent with the Paris Climate Agreement towards individual countries, the built environment, property types and individual assets. The data offers the possibility to evaluate the progress of an asset's operational carbon profile against decarbonisation targets consistent with the 1.5 pathway.

From this data, the risks of asset stranding can be analysed, it's warming potential identified, as well as its performance against its carbon budget.
Benchmarking.WarmingPotentialIntro: bZero converts the carbon emissions profile of the Target Asset into the global warming potential which is expressed in °C. Known as Implied Temperature Rise, it is a TCFD and Bank of England supported metric.

CarbonImpact.EmbodiedCarbonIntro:
Embodied carbon is emitted during the construction process of a building – and later through the ongoing upgrading of the building systems and also as a result of retrofits. Embodied carbon is emitted from the production of the construction materials themselves, with building materials such as steel, concrete and glass being carbon-intensive to produce. Once produced, additional carbon is then emitted in the transportation of materials to site and by machinery used during the construction.

Over the lifecycle of a building, further embodied carbon is emitted as part of upgrading systems and retrofitting. Finally, decommissioning a building at the end of its life creates additional embodied carbon impact.

The World Green Building Council estimates 11% of global emissions come from embodied carbon sources. As new construction activity continues to quicken, in particular in Asia and the Global South, we expect embodied carbon emissions to rise.

Currently there is no regulation of embodied carbon in the European construction industry, however this may change soon, with industry and government in discussions on enhancing current building codes. However, there is precedent emerging in some countries, with Denmark for example, bringing in whole of life carbon emission regulations and a carbon levy on breaches. This includes embodied and operational carbon.
CarbonImpact.OperationalCarbonIntro:
Operational carbon is emitted throughout the operations of a building causing carbon to be released into the atmosphere – primarily through the energy, water and waste it consumes as part of day-to-day operations.

Broadly speaking, over the typical lifecycle of a built asset some 50% of its carbon emissions come from operational carbon sources and 50% from embodied. This profile can differ depending on a range of factors including building type, location and the stage at with the building sits in its lifecycle. For example it's estimated that the embodied carbon in a distribution warehouse was 60% of its total lifetime carbon footprint, whereas a supermarket, which uses a lot more energy, has an embodied carbon content of 20%.

As the built environment becomes more energy efficient, we anticipate in the future a greater proportion of emissions to be caused by embodied carbon.

The World Green Building Council estimates 28% of global emissions come from operational carbon sources.

GreenPlace uses its innovative proprietary software tool called bZero and deep built environment domain expertise to measure, manage and reduce carbon emissions across Scopes 1, 2 & 3.
CarbonImpact.WholeLifeIntro:
bZero assumes 60 years as a whole of life period for a typical building.

By taking the current estimate for the asset's embodied carbon and combining it with an estimate for operational carbon emissions over the next 60 years, bZero estimates the whole of life carbon emissions.

RegulatoryBenchmark.RegulatoryBenchmarkIntro:
Currently, the key regulatory framework for energy and carbon emissions in the UK are Energy Performance Certificates (EPCs)

EPCs estimate how energy efficient a building is and give it a rating from A (very efficient) to G (inefficient).

An EPC also includes information on what the energy efficiency rating could be if the recommended improvements were made and highlights cost effective ways to achieve a better rating.

EPCs are valid for 10 years from the date of issue and are for both residential and commercial buildings.

A commercial building must have an EPC, it its rented out, being marketed for sale, completed construction or if there has been certain changes to the building. In addition, there are certain requirements for the EPC to be physically displayed at the building.

As well as fines being imposed for not having an EPC, there is an additional regulatory framework, known as Minimum Energy Efficiency Standards (MEES). In summary and from April 2023, MEES will be extended to include all existing commercial tenancies as well as new tenancies. It means that a building owner must not grant a new tenancy or continue to let a property unless either:

  1. the property has an Energy Performance Certificate (EPC) rating of at least an E, or
  2. the landlord makes sufficient energy improvements to the property so that it is no longer sub-standard or they can claim a legitimate reason for not doing so.

Failure to comply with these regulations risks a fine of up to £150,0000 dependent upon property type and the extent of the breach. If a breach occurs, details may also be entered onto the publicly accessible part of the PRS Exemptions Register. This carries the risk of adverse publicity for an owner.

Looking forward, the UK government have projected their future intentions for EPCs following April 2023 and is proposing that the minimum EPC rating will increase to C by 2027 and to B by 2030. The government will likely reform and tighten the EPC regulations, including the scope of exemptions and giving Local Authorities the power to inspect commercial buildings.

It is recognised by industry and the Government that EPCs are weak at estimating actual energy consumption of a building. Given this. there are plans to implement a new system in the non-domestic sector that uses actual in use energy related data. That said and for the time being, the EPC framework is the only regulatory tool that the Government has to decarbonise the built environment.

ValueAtCarbonRisk.ValueAtCarbonRiskIntro:
The bZero value @ carbon risk proprietary model uses a range a range of inputs to estimate the % of the current estimated appraised value that is at risk from the market transition to a lower/ zero carbon economy. bZero takes into account economic drivers, market pricing factors, costs and carbon specific assumptions in the value @ carbon risk model.

The % factor represents the scale of the potential fall in the estimated Target Asset value, which in the market is being increasingly known as the brown discount.
